metadata.name: Mercalli #44
metadata.description:
"Earthquakes don't kill people, buildings do." – Unknown

Earthquakes are not just natural disasters, but also human tragedies. They can strike suddenly and violently, leaving behind a trail of destruction and trauma that can last a lifetime. For survivors, the experience of an earthquake can be life changing.

Homes and neighborhoods are reduced to rubble, and the familiar landmarks and memories of a lifetime are wiped away in an instant. In the aftermath of an earthquake, survivors must grapple with the emotional toll of their loss, the uncertainty of the future, and the challenge of rebuilding their lives.

The first step after a disaster is to provide emergency medical care, shelter, and basic necessities like food and water. Once these immediate needs are met, attention can turn to assessing the damage and developing a plan for reconstruction.

The rebuilding process can be a long and challenging journey, as it involves not only repairing physical damage but also restoring the social fabric of affected communities, addressing issues like housing, infrastructure, and economic recovery, as well as addressing the psychological and emotional impact of the disaster on individuals and communities.

It is crucial to rebuild using proper techniques and investing in the right resources to prevent similar disasters from happening in the future. Reconstruction must be done with a focus on resilience, sustainability, and safety. This means taking into consideration the local conditions, the latest research on earthquake-resistant materials and designs, and the needs of the affected communities.

The cost of not investing in proper reconstruction after an earthquake can be immense. Poorly constructed buildings and infrastructure can increase the risk of further damage in the event of another earthquake, leading to more loss of life and property. On the other hand, investing in proper reconstruction can help create a safer and more resilient environment, reducing the impact of future earthquakes and protecting the lives and livelihoods of those who call the affected region home.

For this reason, it is crucial that regions impacted by earthquakes receive immediate and adequate economic and technical support, and that available resources are managed with proper planning and great responsibility.

This generative art project explores the destructive power of earthquakes and seeks to capture the raw emotions of those who have experienced earthquakes and the transformation of their world into a memory.

100% of the primary split is going to @tezquakeaid, Tezos community initiative providing aid to the victims of the catastrophic earthquake that struck Turkey and Syria on February 6, 2023. 
Once again the Tezos community has proven to be special. 💚

Hand coded after midnight.
Powered by p5, matter & chroma.

======> COMMANDS (In Live Mode) <======

Press ‘s’ to save the current output.
The generation takes some time but you can see the simulation and drawing process happening in real-time.

Settings are passed as URL parameters and pressing the following keys, the artwork will regenerate at a different scale:

- 1 -> 1.920x1.080
- 2 -> 4.000x2.252
- 3 -> 6.000x3.378
- 4 -> 8.000x4.504

metadata.name: Ray Tracing Black Holes #39
metadata.description:
Ray tracing black holes in Schwarzschild metric.
The equations of motion of the light beams are integrated using the Runge Kutta method.
The accretion disk is purely generative, no textures are used.
Rendering may take a while since we need to solve the EOM in Schwarzschild for each pixel of the image.

metadata.name: Fluidynamix - Cities #17
metadata.description:
A fluid dynamics messy piece

Each edition generates a trapped city flying through space. To liquify the buildings, move your mouse over them, and use the buttons at the bottom to shape the city by adding or removing buildings, sky taxis, cars and trees. Hold the buttons down for a more speedy edit. 

If you're lucky enough to get a special FX of (f)ireworks, (l)ightshow, (m)eteors or (w)arpspeed, then type the appropriate key to stop/restart the effect. 

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Mustachioed #148
metadata.description:
Who has the chance to have a weird mustache on his face?
Art, personality, politics, religion, power or any other factor has made some mustache models dependent on individuals and takes its name from its first or most famous owner.

metadata.name: Skull Legion #1
metadata.description: In the ruins of an ancient city ravaged by great wars, warriors rise from the ashes—skeletal champions cursed by dark magic. Once noble heroes, they are now bound to serve the shadows of a black enchantment. Every step they take through the desolate city is a trial of strength and will, where traps of dark sorcery lurk at every turn.

metadata.name: kaonashi #7
metadata.description:
Reviewing Memories: Kaonashi, the Wandering Spirit in a Ruined City

In my recollections, Kaonashi is a wandering spirit in a desolate, ruined city. The memories are filled with vivid images and emotions. Kaonashi, draped in tattered garments, roams the empty streets and abandoned structures. The city, ravaged by time, serves as a haunting backdrop. Nature reclaims the urban landscape, adding to the eerie ambiance. Kaonashi's faceless presence exudes sorrow and longing.

metadata.name: Pumpkin Head #41
metadata.description: The creatures observed within the desolate cemetery of the city are commonly known as "pumpkin heads." According to local accounts, these entities are believed to be the most horrifying creatures in the entire city, instilling sheer terror in those who encounter them. It is rumored that the mere sound of their voices has the power to awaken the dormant zombies, causing them to rise from their graves once again.

metadata.name: olho do furacão #16
metadata.description:
No centro o movimento é imperceptível, mas quando olhamos para o extremo ele se move tão rápido quanto nossa percepção pode suportar, o ruído gira e na fusão das abóbadas essa confluência de modulações nos coloca no centro do furacão.

In the center the movement is imperceptible but when we look at the extreme it moves as fast as our perception can carry, the noise swirls and in the merging of the vaults this confluence of modulations places us in the center of the hurricane. 

960x960 for gpus, you can press 'a' to change the resolution to minimal 256x256 recomended to tiny systems, web video synthesizer patchwork made on hydra.ojack.xyz

Fxhash
Wednesday, April 30, 2025
